{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}} {{infobox newspaper | image = | caption = | foundation = 21 February 2000 | owners = [[Gruner + Jahr]] | political = [[Keynesianism]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Von Jan Mallien. |url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/oekonomie/nachrichten/us-oekonom-allan-meltzer-keynes-politik-ist-ausrangiert/6634060-3.html|title=US-Ökonom Allan Meltzer: "Keynes' Politik ist ausrangiert"|language=de|work=Handelsblatt|accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref> | language = [[German language|German]] | ceased publication = 7 December 2012 | headquarters = [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]] | editor = [[Steffen Klusmann]] | price = | audience = |circulation = 103,000 | ISSN = 1615-4118
}} The '''''Financial Times Deutschland''''' was a [[German-language]] financial newspaper based in [[Hamburg]], Germany, published by [[Bertelsmann]]'s [[Gruner + Jahr]] newspaper and magazine division. The daily contained four sections: Business, Politics & Economy, Finance, and Agenda (Comment, Analysis, Sport, Culture). It ceased publication on 7 December 2012.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/dec/07/germany-financial-times-deutschland-closes ''Germany's Financial Times Deutschland closes after huge losses'', Guardian, London, 7 December 2012].Retrieved: 20 December 2012.</ref>
==History and profile== ''Financial Times Deutschland'' was founded at the height of the [[dot-com bubble]] on 21 February 2000<ref name=rom>{{cite web|author=Carsten Croonenbroeck|author2=Roman Matkovskyy|title=Is the Market Held by Institutional Investors? The Disposition Effect Revisited.|url=http://www.wiwi.europa-uni.de/de/forschung/publikationen-projekte/dp/_dokumente/338_Croonenbroeck_Matkovskyy.pdf|work=European University Viadrina Frankfurt|accessdate=3 February 2015|format=Discussion paper. No: 338|date=July 2013}}</ref> as a [[joint venture]] between UK ''[[Financial Times]]'' publisher [[Pearson PLC|Pearson]] and [[Gruner + Jahr]].<ref name="ftd">{{cite web|url=http://www.ftd.de/panorama/leute/:ftd-historie-12-jahre-in-bildern/70126079.html|title=FTD-Historie: 12 Jahre in Bildern|work=Financial Times Deutschland|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="ft">{{cite web|author=Gerrit Wiesmann|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/0c8df1ae-356b-11e2-bd77-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2ENB8wZWR|title=FT Deutschland closure date confirmed|work=Financial Times|date=23 November 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref> The paper's original editor was [[Andrew Gowers]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Gareth Jones|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/12/07/uk-germany-newspaper-idUKBRE8B60J820121207|title=Gloom and jokes as Financial Times Deutschland laid to rest|work=Reuters|date=7 December 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref> Circulation grew to 103,000 readers by the third quarter of 2007, however the paper never turned a profit.<ref name="guard"/> At the beginning of 2008 Pearson sold their stake to Gruner + Jahr for €10m and an agreement to receive annual licence fees of €500,000.<ref name="ft"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Gruner + Jahr Becomes Sole Shareholder of FINANCIAL TIMES DEUTSCHLAND|url=http://www.guj.de/en/press/press-releases/gruner-jahr-becomes-sole-shareholder-of-financial-times-deutschland/|accessdate=3 May 2015|work=Gruner + Jahr|date=29 January 2008}}</ref> Following the sale to Gruner + Jahr, the ''FT Deutschland'' became no longer subject to any editorial control from the ''Financial Times''.<ref>{{cite web|author=John McDermott|url=http://ftalphaville.ft.com/blog/2011/10/03/691471/papandreou-mulls-resignation-says-ft-deutschland/|title=Papandreou mulls resignation, says FT Deutschland|work=Financial Times|date=3 October 2011|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref>
The circulations of the daily in 2008, in 2009 and in 2010 were 112,238 copies, 103,276 copies and 103,609 copies, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=National newspapers total circulation|url=http://www.ifabc.org/site/assets/media/National-Newspapers_total-circulation_IFABC_09-07-12.xls|work=International Federation of Audit Bureaux of Circulations|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>
==Closure== In November 2012, Gruner + Jahr announced the closure of ''Financial Times Deutschland'' as part of a restructuring of their economics publishing division, having failed to find a buyer for the title.<ref name="guard">{{cite web|author=Nadine Schimroszik |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/nov/23/financial-times-deutschland-close-germany|title=Financial Times Deutschland to close|work=The Guardian |date=23 November 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref> G + J estimate that the ''FTD'' made a cumulative loss of €250m over its 12-year life.<ref name="ft"/> The last print edition was published on 7 December 2012<ref>{{cite news|author=Shannon Smith|title=In Germany, the price of journalism|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/in-germany-the-price-of-journalism/|accessdate=25 April 2015|work=ZD Net|date=29 November 2012|location=Berlin}}</ref> displaying an all black front cover featuring the words "Endlich schwarz" ("At last, black" alluding to never having booked a profit since inception).<ref>{{cite web|author=Rob Wile|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ft-deutschland-final-issue-2012-12|title=FT Deutschland Final Issue|work=Business Insider|date=7 December 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref> The final issue was named ''Final Time Deutschland''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Europe’s newspapers are dying too|url=http://www.cjr.org/behind_the_news/european_newspapers_in_dire_st.php?page=all|work=Columbia Journalism Review|accessdate=6 October 2013|author=Alison Langley|date=12 December 2012}}</ref> The paper's internet presence was also closed.
The final [[editing|editor]] was Steffen Klusmann, who had taken the role on 1 August 2004 following the defection of [[Christoph Keese]] to rival ''[[Welt am Sonntag]]''.
Following the closure, memorabilia from the newspaper was auctioned off, with the proceeds being donated to [[Freedom of the press|press freedom]] advocates [[Reporters Without Borders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business/21567952-curtains-or-see-you-world-wide-web-so-farewell-then-ftd |title=German newspapers: So farewell then, FTD|work=The Economist|date=8 December 2012|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref>
