'''Stuart Pearson''' (born c.1984)<ref name="it-1030">
{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2008/1030/1225320616121.html |title=Interest shown in Taggart properties |date=30 October 2008 |first=Barry |last=O'Halloran |work=[[The Irish Times]] }}
</ref> is an Irish convenience store worker<ref name="sweet_shop">
{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0515/1224246568925.html |title='Billionaire investor' is sweet-shop owner |last=Parsons |first=Michael |date=15 May 2009 |work=[[Irish Times]] |accessdate=17 May 2009}}
</ref> whose name was linked to a number of investment rumours in 2008. All of which turned out to be a hoax.<ref name="LI-20100803-1">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/sweet-shop-swizzler-claimed-he-had-billions-but-he-only-had-hundreds-and-thousands-1687784.html  |title='Sweet Shop Swizzler Claimed He Had Billions' |last=McKittrick |first=David |date=20 May 2009 |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=3 August 2010}}
</ref>

==Biography==
He was born in [[Arklow]] where his family lived in Templerainey<ref name="wicklow-1224">
{{cite news |url=http://www.wicklowpeople.ie/news/arklow-highflyer-in-aer-lingus-bid-1585736.html |title=Arklow highflyer in Aer Lingus bid |last=Coleman |first=Deborah |date=24 December 2008 |work=[[Wicklow People]] |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref> and owned a [[Burmah Oil|Burmah]] [[petrol station]].<ref name="wicklow">
{{cite news |title=Arklow C.B.S.: Not all doom and gloom |url=http://www.wicklowpeople.ie/local-notes/arklow-cbs-1612897.html |date=21 January 2009 |work=[[Wicklow People]] |page=1 |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref> By 1998 they moved to [[Carlow]] where he claimed to own 'The Foundry' [[nightclub]].<ref name="wicklow"/> (In fact, The Foundry is part of the Dinn Rí Hotel complex<ref>
{{cite web |url=http://www.dinnri.com/intro.htm |title=Dinn Rí Entertainment Complex – profile |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref> owned by the McLoughlin family.<ref>
{{cite news |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/carlownationalist/2008/02/27/story33709.asp |title=Days of town- centre parking at Plás na Saoirse numbered  |date=27 February 2008 |work=[[Carlow Nationalist]] |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref>) Pearson qualified as an accountant in [[Portlaoise]] c.2008.<ref name="wicklow-1224"/> He moved with his wife and two daughters to [[County Kilkenny]],<ref name="kk2908"/> where he rented a house in [[Goresbridge]]<ref name="it0515"/> and worked in a convenience store in [[Graiguenamanagh]].<ref name="kk2908"/><ref name="it0515">
{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0515/1224246568925.html |title='Billionaire investor' is sweet-shop owner |last=Parsons |first=Michael |date=15 May 2009|work=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref> He was attacked in a robbery on the shop in January 2008.<ref>
{{cite news |title=Shopkeeper attacked in terrifying robbery |url=http://www.carlowpeople.ie/news/shopkeeper-attacked-1263392.html |date=9 January 2008 |work=[[Carlow People]] |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref><ref>
{{cite news |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/carlownationalist/2008/01/16/story33395.asp |title='Give us €10,000... we have your wife and two daughters' |date=16 January 2008 |work=[[Carlow Nationalist]] |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref> In May 2009,  ''[[The Irish Times]]'' reported that he had [[legal separation|separated]] from his wife, who claimed to have no knowledge of his business dealings; and that locals in Goresbridge were surprised by and sceptical of the reports of Pearson's extreme claim of wealth.<ref name="it0515"/> The ''[[Irish Daily Mail]]'' had expressed similar scepticism in December 2008.<ref>
{{cite news |title=Isaac Bickerstaffe |date=19 December 2008 |work=[[Irish Daily Mail]] |page=17 |quote=Stuart Pearson is the reputed multi-millionaire in question, but quite how he made his fortune is hardly clear – until recently, he has been running his own convenience store in the town. }}
</ref>

==Purported investments==
According to interviews, Pearson inherited money from relatives' land in 2003.<ref name="wicklow"/><ref name="kk2908">
{{cite news |url=http://www.kilkennypeople.ie/news/Young-gun-investor-eyes-property.4638840.jp |title=Young gun investor eyes property giant |last=Keys |first=Laura |date=29 October 2008 |work=[[Kilkenny People]] |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref><ref name="ind-2510">
{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/hotshot-developer-eyes-taggart-businesses-1510068.html |title=Hotshot developer eyes Taggart businesses  |date=25 October 2008 |first=John |last=Mulligan |work=[[Irish Independent]] }}
</ref> This was held by [[trustee]]s till 2008,<ref name="kk2908"/> who invested it in property, mostly commercial property, in Ireland and Britain.<ref name="it-1030"/><ref name="kk2908"/><ref name="it-1107">
{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2008/1107/1225925539902.html |title=Potential Taggart buyer contacts PwC |date=7 November 2008 |first=Barry |last=O'Halloran |work=[[The Irish Times]] }}
</ref> Pearson Holdings and Acquisitions was reported to have property in counties [[County Carlow|Carlow]], [[County Wicklow|Wicklow]], [[County Dublin|Dublin]], and north [[County Kildare|Kildare]].<ref name="carlow">
{{cite news |url=http://www.carlowpeople.ie/news/bid-for-taggart-holdings-1513572.html |title=Bid for Taggart Holdings |date=28 October 2008 |work=[[Carlow People]] }}
</ref> It reportedly paid £340m in 2004 and £600m later for retail property in London;<ref name="ind-2510"/> bought some units in [[Grafton Street]], Dublin;<ref name="ind-2510"/> and earned €600m<ref name="ind-1311">
{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/pearson-to-bid-soon-for-taggart-1537101.html |title=Pearson to bid soon for Taggart |date=13 November 2008 |first=John |last=Mulligan |work=[[Irish Independent]] }}
</ref> or €800m<ref name="it-1218">
{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2008/1218/breaking59.html |title=Pearson Holdings emerges as possible Aer Lingus investor |date=18 December 2008 |first=Barry |last=O'Halloran |work=[[The Irish Times]] }}
</ref> from an investment in New York City.

In October 2008, Pearson was reported to have been negotiating to buy Taggart Holdings, a housebuilding firm based in [[Northern Ireland]]<ref name="ind-1311"/> which was in [[administration (law)|administration]] with debts reported at €150m.<ref name="it-1030"/><ref name="kk2908"/><ref name="it-1107"/> In December 2008, it was reported that he might invest in [[Aer Lingus]],<ref name="it-1218"/> and subsequently that he might launch a [[takeover]] offer of up to €900m, funded from a [[war chest]] of €1.5–2b.<ref name="ind-2012">
{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/pearson-to-battle-ryanair-in-outright-bid-for-aer-lingus-1581919.html |title=Pearson to battle Ryanair in outright bid for Aer Lingus |date=20 December 2008 |first=John |last=Mulligan |work=[[Irish Independent]] }}
</ref> In 2009, he was reported to be planning to build a [[retirement village]] in Arklow, and to start an [[insurance company]].<ref name="wicklow-1224"/> He is reported to support many charities in Carlow and Kilkenny, and in April 2009 was producing a DVD showcasing investment opportunities in the region.<ref>
{{cite news |url=http://www.advertiser.ie/carlowfirst/article/11191 |title=Millionaire businessman to make DVD to attract new business |last=Coogan |first=Naoise |date=17 April 2009 |work=Carlow First |publisher=Galway Advertiser |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref><ref>
{{cite web |url=http://www.kilkennyalive.com/story/worldwide-promotion-kilkenny |title=Worldwide promotion for Kilkenny |last=Hurley |first=Sean |date=27 April 2009 |work=Kilkenny Alive |accessdate=15 May 2009}}
</ref>
All this turned out to be a hoax which Pearson started to get attention.

